la(u)ndres</i> ‘Flanders’, denoting someone from Flanders, a historical region covering parts of modern-day Belgium, France, and the Netherlands. Compare   Fleming  ."]},{"name":"Fleeman","meanings":["English: variant of   Fleming  ."]},{"name":"Flemming","meanings":["German: ethnic name for someone from Flanders, Middle High German <i>vlaeminc</i>. People from Flanders spread throughout Germany, as well as England, in the Middle Ages as clothmakers and dyers.","English: variant of   Fleming  ."]},{"name":"Flamenco","meanings":["Spanish: ethnic name from <i>flamenco</i> ‘Fleming, Flemish person’ (see   Fleming  )."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs. William Fleming was born in 1310, in Fermoy, County Cork, Ireland. She married William Fleming in 1328, in Fermoy, County Cork, Ireland. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter."},"et":{"1310–":"1310–Surnud","1305–Male":"1305–Surnud","1328–1350":"1328–1350","1310–Female":"1310–Surnud","1305":"1305","1310":"1310","1350":"1350","1328":"1328","Fermoy, Cork, Munster, Ireland":"Fermoy, County Cork, Iirimaa"},"fi":{"1310–":"1310–Kuollut","1305–Male":"1305–Kuollut","1328–1350":"1328–1350","1310–Female":"1310–Kuollut","1305":"1305","1310":"1310","1350":"1350","1328":"1328","Fer